# Tell, Don't Ask

Objects should **do** work, not expose state for others to decide.

## Principle

```java
// ❌ ASK — controller inspects and mutates
if (project.getMedias().size() < 10) {
    project.getMedias().add(media);
    projects.update(project);
}

// ✅ TELL — project enforces its own rules
project.attachMedia(media);
projects.save(project);
```

## Domain Behavior Belongs on Domain Types

```java
// ❌ ASK — service calculates from exposed state
long max = project.getClips().stream()
    .mapToLong(Clip::getEndTime)
    .max().orElse(0);
project.setDuration(max);

// ✅ TELL
project.recalculateDuration();
```

## Encapsulate Collections

```java
// ❌ ASK — caller can break invariants
public List<Media> getMedias() { return medias; }

// ✅ TELL — unmodifiable view + mutation methods
public List<Media> medias() { return List.copyOf(medias); }
public void attachMedia(Media media) { ... }
```

## Avoid Feature Envy

If a method mostly reads another object's getters, move the behavior there:

```java
// ❌ Feature envy in service
boolean canRender = timeline.getTracks().stream()
    .anyMatch(MediaTrack::hasClips);

// ✅ TELL the object that owns the data
boolean canRender = timeline.hasContent();
```

## When Getters Are OK

- Serialization (JSON, Mongo POJO codec, Qute templates).
- Infrastructure mapping at boundaries.
- Simple value object accessors (`screenSize.width()`).

Do not chain getters across layers to make decisions — add a method on the object that owns the data.

## Law of Demeter

```java
// ❌ train wreck
project.getMedias().get(0).getMimeType()

// ✅ ask the project
project.mimeTypeOfFirstMedia()
```
